SIMPLE: increment
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Increment
<hw>In"cre*ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>incrementum</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incr⟦eacute⟧ment</ets>. See
<er>Increase</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or process of increasing; growth in bulk,
quantity, number, value, or amount; augmentation; enlargement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The seminary that furnisheth matter for the formation and
<qex>increment</qex> of animal and vegetable bodies.</q>
<rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A nation, to be great, ought to be compressed in its
<qex>increment</qex> by nations more civilized than itself.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Matter added; increase; produce; production; --
opposed to <ant>decrement</ant>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Large
<xex>increment</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J. Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The increase of a variable
quantity or fraction from its present value to its next ascending value;
the finite quantity, generally variable, by which a variable quantity is
increased.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>An amplification without strict
climax, <as>as in the following passage:</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Finally, brethren, whatsoever things are true, whatsoever things
are honest, whatsoever things are just, whatsoever things are pure,
whatsoever things are lovely, whatsoever things are of good report, . .
. think on these things.</q> <rj><qau>Phil. iv. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Infinitesimal increment</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>an infinitesimally small variation considered in Differential
Calculus. See <er>Calculus</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Method of
increments</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a calculus founded on the
properties of the successive values of variable quantities and their
differences or increments. It differs from the <xex>method of
fluxions</xex> in treating these differences as finite, instead of
infinitely small, and is equivalent to the calculus of <xex>finite
differences</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incremental</ent>⟦br⟧
